**Primitive Data Types**
Primitive data types in Java store simple values and do not contain methods. They are stored in stack memory, making them fast and lightweight.

Stored directly as values
Fast and memory-efficient
Default values depend on type
Cannot be null
Not suitable for collections like ArrayList
Java Primitive Types


| Primitive Type | Size    | Default Value | Example Value |
| :---           | :---    | :---          | :---          |
| `byte`         | 1 byte  | `0`           | `10`          |
| `short`        | 2 bytes | `0`           | `20`          |
| `int`          | 4 bytes | `0`           | `100`         |
| `long`         | 8 bytes | `0L`          | `1000L`       |
| `float`        | 4 bytes | `0.0f`        | `3.14f`       |
| `double`       | 8 bytes | `0.0`         | `99.99`       |
| `char`         | 2 bytes | `'\u0000'`    | `'A'`         |
| `boolean`      | —       | `false`       | `true`        |



**Wrapper Classes**
Wrapper classes convert primitive types into objects, The default value of the wrapper class is null as they are objects. Wrapper Classes enabling features such as
Usage in Java Collections (e.g., ArrayList<Integer>)
Serialization
Working with generic classes
Using utility methods (e.g., Integer.parseInt())
Wrapper Classes for Each Primitive


| Primitive Type | Wrapper Class |
| :---           | :---          |
| `byte`         | `Byte`        |
| `short`        | `Short`       |
| `int`          | `Integer`     |
| `long`         | `Long`        |
| `float`        | `Float`       |
| `double`       | `Double`      |
| `char`         | `Character`   |
| `boolean`      | `Boolean`     |


**Primitive Data Types vs Wrapper Classes:**


| Primitive Data Types           | Wrapper Classes                                |
| :---                          | :---                                           |
| Fast and memory efficient      | Slightly slower (creates an object)            |
| Cannot be null                 | Can be null                                    |
| Cannot be serialized directly  | Can be serialized directly                     |
| Not suitable for collections   | Required for Java Collections (e.g., ArrayList) |
| Used in basic arithmetic/loops | Used when methods return objects or `null`     |




